- Dislikes: bright, dry center‑front midrange lead production; crystalline, tightly stacked harmony‑first overdubs; minimal ambience or narrow staging; glossy pop polish or heavy multiband vocal compression; brick‑wall limiting/over‑compression; restrained/buried bass, gated/over‑processed drums, overly short reverbs; thin, lyric‑forward mixes that sacrifice dynamic headroom.
2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those preferences/dislikes
- Sleeping With The Past Remastered:
  - Pros relative to my likes: tape‑warm analogue timbre, preserved transient snap, generous headroom, restrained limiting and natural drums, full‑length solos and spacious stereo depth — these match my desire for low‑compression tape warmth and preserved dynamics.
  - Cons relative to my dislikes: it is explicitly “piano‑first” with tactile close‑miked piano and “intimate yet presence‑forward vocals” plus “lush harmonies.” That signals a center‑front, instrument/vocal focus (close, presence‑forward) and harmony emphasis, which conflicts with my preference for guitar‑first, room‑miked, wide front‑to‑back imaging and my dislike of harmony‑first, crystalline stacked overdubs and voice‑forward, lyric‑centric mixes. The close‑miked piano and presence‑forward vocals reduce the roomy ambience and guitar‑forward staging I prize.
- Double‑album of extended live and studio takes:
  - Pros relative to my likes: immediate, raw room ambience; tape‑like warmth; preserved transients and generous headroom; minimal vocal processing; wide dynamic contrast; roomy stereo imaging and long‑form sequencing; tactile bass/keys and an avoidance of voice‑forward, radio single clichés. These map directly to my priorities: roomy front‑to‑back imaging and generous ambience, minimal vocal processing, long takes and extended performances (which encourage spontaneous solos and riffing), and preserved dynamics/headroom. The “raw room ambience” and extended takes strongly imply room‑miked instruments and live spontaneity — exactly what I seek for guitar‑first, riff‑centric listening.
  - Minor unknown: the description names bass/keys explicitly and doesn’t call out guitar, but the combination of raw live ambience, extended takes and minimal vocal processing strongly favors organic, room‑captured guitar layers and spontaneous solos over a glossy, vocal‑centric pop approach.
3) Decision and rationale
I choose the Double‑album of extended live and studio takes. Both candidates share important technical virtues I care about (tape warmth, preserved transients, generous headroom and restrained limiting), but the double‑album aligns much more closely with the structural and staging preferences that matter most to me: raw room ambience, wide imaging, minimal vocal processing, long‑form sequencing and an avoidance of voice‑forward, harmony‑centric pop production. Those features are the practical enablers of the immersive, guitar‑first, riff‑and‑solo‑forward listening experience I prefer.
I reject the Sleeping With The Past Remaster because its piano‑first, close‑miked presentation and “intimate/presence‑forward” vocals with “lush harmonies” run counter to core dislikes (center‑front, harmony‑first, vocal‑forward mixes and tightly stacked overdubs) and to my desire for room‑miked, guitar‑forward staging. Even though it ticks many mastering boxes (tape warmth, preserved transients, headroom), its instrument/vocal prioritization and close‑miked intimacy make it a less faithful match for the roomy, riff‑centric, front‑to‑back listening experience I value.

